<subSubSection id="00A7655CFF8DFFECFF72FF5D78C1FC49" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" type="description">
<paragraph id="480236D7FF8DFFECFF72FF5D7826F889" blockId="4.[166,1225,175,1034]" box="[219,1070,175,202]" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">
D i s t r i b u t i o n: 
<collectingCountry id="30AA7647FF8DFFECFE33FF427E07F88A" box="[410,527,175,201]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2C2C4B26FF8DFFECFDB7FF427F18F889" author="Mohrig, W. &amp; Krivosheina, N. &amp; Mamaev, B." box="[542,784,175,202]" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" pagination="427 - 445" refId="ref8132" refString="Mohrig, W., Krivosheina, N., Mamaev, B. 1989 b. Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Trauermucken (Diptera, Sciaridae) der Sowjetunion Teil XIII: Gattung Bradysia, Serie 2. Zoologische Jahrbucher, Abteilung Fur Systematik, Okologie und Geographie der Tiere, 116 (4), 427 - 445." type="journal article" year="1989">Mohrig et al., 1989b</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry id="30AA7647FF8DFFECFC8DFF427F8CF88A" box="[804,900,175,201]" name="Ukraine" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis id="7AC9EAC5FF8DFFECFC3CFF427815F88A" bold="true" box="[917,1053,175,201]" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">first record</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="480236D7FF8DFFECFF72FF227E92FA2A" blockId="4.[166,1225,175,1034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">
Diagnosis. Male imagoes reach 
<quantity id="8F459B32FF8DFFECFDC3FF227EB9F8A9" box="[618,689,207,234]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
in length. Eye bridge consists of 2–3 rows of ommatidia (
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFE9CFF027D89F94A" box="[309,385,239,265]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 14</figureCitation>
). The 4 
<superScript id="BFC89B9FFF8DFFECFE7DFF037DEAF8BF" attach="left" box="[468,482,238,252]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">th</superScript>
flagellomere barely twice as long as wide, with a very short neck and short setose (significantly shorter than the flagellomere width, 
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFC14FEE27800F96A" box="[957,1032,271,297]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 17</figureCitation>
). Maxillary palp consists of 3 palpomeres. Basal palpomere (p 
<subScript id="D4393492FF8DFFECFD16FEAF7ECFF913" attach="left" box="[703,711,322,336]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">1</subScript>
) big with clearly deepened sensory pit and 3 setae (one longer and stronger than the others); p 
<subScript id="D4393492FF8DFFECFD57FE8F7F0EF933" attach="left" box="[766,774,354,368]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">2</subScript>
and p 
<subScript id="D4393492FF8DFFECFCE6FE8F7F5FF933" attach="left" box="[847,855,354,368]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">3</subScript>
together slightly longer than p 
<subScript id="D4393492FF8DFFECFB69FE8F78C0F933" attach="left" box="[1216,1224,354,368]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">1</subScript>
(
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFF07FE827CF2F9CA" box="[174,250,367,393]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Thorax, gonocoxite and legs almost the same dark color. Mesonotum quite coarse and dark setose, with very strong lateral and 2 scutellar setae (
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFCD4FE627FB3F9EA" box="[893,955,399,425]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Wing slightly brown; c longer than a half of w; y shorter than a half of x, with 1–2 macrotrichia; M-fork very short; posterior wing veins indistinct (
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFDC1FE227EBDF9A9" box="[616,693,463,490]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 16</figureCitation>
). Hypopygium short, dark and heavily setose (
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFF07FE027CF3FA4A" box="[174,251,495,521]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Gonostyli relatively small with weak and dorsal strong setae — claw-like dorsal spines, 7–9 loosely standing coarse subapical setae and 2–3 loosely standing awl shaped setae on the end of the apical third (
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFDECFDC27E99FA0A" box="[581,657,559,585]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Tegmen wider than its length, with a large field of multi-tipped teeth (Mohrig et al., 1989).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="480236D7FF8DFFECFF72FD827D78FAA9" blockId="4.[166,1225,175,1034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">
<taxonomicName id="8FBD4D54FF8DFFECFF72FD827DC1FACA" authorityName="Mohrig &amp; Krivosheina" authorityYear="1989" box="[219,457,623,649]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Bradysia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microspina">
<emphasis id="7AC9EAC5FF8DFFECFF72FD827DC1FACA" box="[219,457,623,649]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">Bradysia microspina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a small species with very small dorsal spines, which are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="8FBD4D54FF8DFFECFE83FD7D7E77FAEA" authority="(Meigen, 1818)" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1818" box="[298,639,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Bradysia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="7AC9EAC5FF8DFFECFE83FD7D7DC9FAEA" box="[298,449,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">B. nitidicollis</emphasis>
(Meigen, 1818)
</taxonomicName>
. From 
<taxonomicName id="8FBD4D54FF8DFFECFD78FD7D7F61FAEA" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1818" box="[721,873,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Bradysia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="7AC9EAC5FF8DFFECFD78FD7D7F61FAEA" box="[721,873,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">B. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it differs by the much smaller dorsal spine, pressed setosity of flagellomeres and well distinguished shorter M-fork (
<bibRefCitation id="2C2C4B26FF8DFFECFB2AFD427D6BFAA9" author="Mohrig, W. &amp; Krivosheina, N. &amp; Mamaev, B." pageId="4" pageNumber="333" pagination="427 - 445" refId="ref8132" refString="Mohrig, W., Krivosheina, N., Mamaev, B. 1989 b. Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Trauermucken (Diptera, Sciaridae) der Sowjetunion Teil XIII: Gattung Bradysia, Serie 2. Zoologische Jahrbucher, Abteilung Fur Systematik, Okologie und Geographie der Tiere, 116 (4), 427 - 445." type="journal article" year="1989">Mohrig et al., 1989 b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="480236D7FF8DFFECFF72FD1D78C1FC49" blockId="4.[166,1225,175,1034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">
Note. The length of y in the studied specimen exceeds a half of length of x, which does not agree with the original description (see above). Tibial organ of t 
<quantity id="8F459B32FF8DFFECFB93FCCF786EFB6A" box="[1082,1126,783,816]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" unit="in" value="1.0">
<subScript id="D4393492FF8DFFECFB93FCCF784AFB73" attach="left" box="[1082,1090,802,816]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">1</subScript>
in
</quantity>
present specimen consists of 6 setae in comb-like row (
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFD7CFCC27F2AFB0A" box="[725,802,815,841]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Studied male imago 
<quantity id="8F459B32FF8DFFECFB82FCC2788EFB09" box="[1067,1158,815,842]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" unit="mm" value="2.3">2.3 mm</quantity>
long, wing 
<quantity id="8F459B32FF8DFFECFF40FCA27D4AFB29" box="[233,322,847,874]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity id="8F459B32FF8DFFECFE15FCA27E10FB29" box="[444,536,847,874]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="333" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
wide, y of one wing with 5 macrotrichia (
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFBA6FCA27855FB29" box="[1039,1117,847,874]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 16</figureCitation>
), but the other wing bears only 1 macrotrichia on y (see black arrow on 
<figureCitation id="D0862A52FF8DFFECFCD2FC827FCCFBC9" box="[891,964,879,906]" captionStart="Figs 9–17" captionStartId="3.[174,213,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[228,1175,789,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-255@3.[208,1190,771,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9–17. Bradysia microspina, male: 9 — thorax, lateral view; 10 — hypopygium, ventral view; 11 —anterior apex of fore tibia (t 1) with tibial organ, lateral view; 12 — gonostylus, ventral view; 13 — maxillary palp, lateral view; 14 — eye bridge, frontal view; 15 — 1 distal macrotrichia on y (black arrow shows); 16 — wing, dorsal view; 17 — fourth flagellomere, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455632/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Biometric indexes of studied specimen: width/length of wing = 0.41; stM/M-fork = 1.05–1.07; R 
<subScript id="D4393492FF8DFFECFBA6FC4F781FFBF3" attach="right" box="[1039,1047,930,944]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="333">1</subScript>
/R = 0.48–0.55; x/y = 1.41–1.47; stCuA/x = 0.66–0.67; c/w = 0.61–0.62. Length of spur/width of tibia: leg 1 = 1.14–1.22, leg 2 = 1.32–1.36; leg 3 = 1.25–1.38. Length of metatarsus/length of tibia: leg 1 = 0.49–0.50, leg 2 = 0.45–0.49, leg 3 = 0.44–0.46. Length of tibia 3/length of thorax 1.24–1.25.
</paragraph>
